Actually, looking at it again more carefully:

```javascript
function is_parent(path, elements) {
	let i = path.length;
	while (i--) {
		const parent = path[i];
		if (parent.type === 'SvelteElement') return true; // unknown, play it safe, so we don't warn
		if (parent.type === 'RegularElement') {
			return elements.includes(parent.name);  // <-- This is the bug!
		}
	}
	return false;
}
```

The bug is that when it finds a `RegularElement`, it immediately returns `elements.includes(parent.name)`. This means:
- If the first RegularElement IS in the list, it returns true ✓
- If the first RegularElement is NOT in the list, it returns false ✗ (should continue checking)

For example, with `<dialog><div><input>`, when checking the input:
- It finds `div` as the first RegularElement
- It checks if `div` is in `['dialog']` → false
- It returns false immediately, never checking the `dialog` ancestor

